data.content:
Three things break in EF Core 10. Here's each one with the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — no longer takes an expression tree

The API now accepts `Action<SetPropertyCalls<Blog>>` instead of `Expression<Func<...>>`. Your manual expression tree construction won't compile. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
// EF Core 10 — just use a regular lambda with conditionals
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

All the `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` machinery can be deleted.

---

### 2. Complex type column names are now uniquified & nested paths changed

Two changes hit you:

- **Shared property names** (e.g., `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street`) now get a numeric suffix to disambiguate. A migration will try to rename columns.
- **Nested complex types** now use the full path: `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City` (was `BillingAddress_City`).

**Fix:** Pin the original column names explicitly so no migration renames anything:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, ab =>
    {
        ab.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
        // ... other properties
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ab =>
    {
        ab.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested complex types:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, pb =>
    {
        pb.ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress, ab =>
        {
            ab.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

After configuring, run `dotnet ef migrations add VerifyNoChanges` — it should produce an empty migration.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on this interface now has an additional `string logCommandText` parameter (redacted SQL safe for logging). Your custom implementation must add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection, DbCommand command,
        DbContext context, Guid commandId, Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on this interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) — they all gained the same parameter.
